  "notes": {
    "greeting": "For You, AmirAbbas",
    "cards": [
      {
        "icon": "🧠",
        "title": "Three Days Is the Plan, Not the Limit",
        "body": "You have five-plus days available, and we're deliberately using three. Your stress level is running high, and stress eats the same recovery your muscles need to grow. Spaced this way, every session is performed at full output — that's what drives progress. Adding extra gym days right now would slow your results, not speed them up."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🛌",
        "title": "Sleep Is Your Edge",
        "body": "Your 7–8 hours of quality sleep is the single reason you can train this hard with a demanding life. Protect it like a training session — especially the nights before gym days. If a rough week cuts your sleep short, drop one or two of the lighter sets that session and keep the big lifts intact."
      },
      {
        "icon": "⏱",
        "title": "The Slow Lowering Is the Work",
        "body": "Leg press, bench press, curls — the 3-second lowering written on them is where muscle is built and joints get conditioned. If you can't control the descent for the full three seconds, the weight is too heavy. Lowering fast to lift more defeats the entire point of this cycle."
      },
      {
        "icon": "📊",
        "title": "Log Every Working Set",
        "body": "Cycle 2 will be built directly from this cycle's numbers. After each exercise, record the weight in the app — every working set, every session. Weeks 1–2 are for finding the right loads; Weeks 3–5 are for nudging them up while the control stays perfect."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🏃",
        "title": "If You Run This Cycle",
        "body": "Running is welcome, but keep it easy — a pace where you could hold a conversation, no more than two short runs a week. Avoid running hard the day before a lower-body session. Done this way, your cardio supports recovery instead of competing with it."
